          "body": "Verse 7 introduces a gratitude that is grounded in experience: 'I will bless the Lord who has counseled me.' The blessing of God (*barakh*) is the creature's response to the Creator's generosity, and here the specific generosity is divine counsel — practical wisdom for the life in front of David. The nighttime instruction of his *kilyah* (translated 'mind' in NASB; literally 'kidneys,' understood in Hebrew anthropology as the seat of deep emotion and conscience) points to the interior word received in stillness when external noise subsides. From this counsel flows the habitual posture of verse 8: 'I have set the Lord continually before me.' The word *tamid* (continually, always) marks this as an unbroken discipline, not a momentary experience. And the result is stated as a logical inference: 'Because He is at my right hand, I will not be shaken.' Verse 9 draws the experiential corollary: the unshaken person is a glad person — heart, tongue (here *kavod*, glory/honor, a metonym for the whole person), and body all participate in the security that flows from God's presence. The integration of emotion, speech, and body signals that biblical joy is not a private interior state but an embodied reality."
