        "excerpt": "Preserve me, O God, for I take refuge in You. I said to the Lord, 'You are my Lord; I have no good besides You.'",
        "body": "The psalm opens with a petition that is simultaneously a declaration of theology. 'Preserve me' (*shamar*, 'guard me') is urgent, but it is not despairing — it is addressed to the specific God in whom David is already hiding. The causal 'for I take refuge in You' makes clear that the petition flows from a prior act of trust, not from terror alone. David is not approaching God as a stranger; he is running to the fortress he already knows.\n\nVerse 2 is the psalm's confessional foundation. The name *Adonai* (Lord, sovereign) marks this as a declaration of submission, not merely affection. And the absolute claim 'I have no good besides You' is one of the most radical statements in the entire Psalter. It does not say God is the greatest good among goods — it says He is the condition of all good whatever. Every genuine good is derivate from and located in God; nothing that presents itself as an alternative source of good actually delivers what it promises. The false gods of verse 4 are implicitly answered before they are named: they cannot offer what they do not have, and all real good belongs to Yahweh.\n\nCalvin notes on this verse: David's declaration is the 'foundation of true religion' — the acknowledgment that God is sufficient and that nothing outside Him can satisfy the soul. This is not asceticism (denying the goodness of creation) but a proper ordering: created goods are genuinely good as reflections of God's goodness but cannot substitute for the Giver. When a created good is made a *refuge* in place of God, it becomes an idol — and verse 4 shows where that leads.\n\nFor the reader of Acts, this verse takes on additional resonance. The One who perfectly embodied 'I have no good besides You' — who in Gethsemane surrendered even the avoidance of death to the Father's will — is the same One whose death and resurrection verse 10 ultimately prophesies. The confession of verse 2 is fully realized only in Christ.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chasah* (take refuge) is consistently used in the Psalter for the act of fleeing to God in danger (Pss 2:12; 5:11; 7:1; 31:1). *Tov* (good) is the same word used seven times in Genesis 1 for the goodness of creation — David claims that the source of all that goodness is his inheritance."
