        "excerpt": "As for the saints who are in the earth, they are the majestic ones in whom is all my delight. The sorrows of those who have bartered for another god will be multiplied.",
        "body": "Verses 3 and 4 form a pair that defines David's social world by two simultaneous movements: delight in the covenant community and refusal of the idolatrous one. This is not merely religious preference — it is a description of two incompatible ways of life with two incompatible outcomes.\n\nThe 'saints' (*qedoshim*, holy ones) are called *addirim* — 'majestic ones' or 'glorious ones,' a word used of the mighty waves of the sea (Ps 93:4) and of the nobles of the land. David sees the covenant community with theological eyes: their greatness is not social but spiritual, their dignity derived from the God to whom they belong. His 'delight' (*chephets*) in them is the same word used of God's own delight — to share delight in the saints is to see them as God sees them. The New Testament fulfillment runs through Hebrews 11's 'great cloud of witnesses' and John's vision of the saints in white: the community of the faithful is a treasure the believing soul recognizes as beautiful.\n\nThe contrast in verse 4 is deliberate and severe. Those who 'barter for another god' — the Hebrew is literally 'hasten after another,' implying an eager, market-oriented pursuit of substitute deities — multiply their own sorrows (*atstsevet*, the curse-word of Genesis 3). Idolatry is not neutral religious preference; it returns the worshiper to the Edenic curse. The double refusal — no blood-libations, no divine names on the lips — is comprehensive. The ancient world ran on ritual and invocation: to pour a drink-offering was to feed a deity, to speak its name was to activate its claim. David refuses both. He will not feed what he will not serve, and he will not name what he will not follow.\n\nPeter Davids's principle from James 1 applies here: the community you choose reveals the God you have. The two verses are the social and communal consequence of the theological confession in verse 2.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qadosh* (holy/saint) shares its root with the messianic title *chasid* in verse 10 — the community of 'holy ones' (v.3) and the singular 'Holy One' (v.10) are linguistically related, suggesting that the covenant community reflects the character of their representative head. *Atstsevet* (sorrows, v.4) is the Genesis 3:16-17 curse-word — its appearance here is almost certainly deliberate."
