        "excerpt": "The Lord is the portion of my inheritance and my cup; You support my lot. The lines have fallen to me in pleasant places; indeed, my heritage is beautiful to me.",
        "body": "Verses 5 and 6 deploy the full vocabulary of Mosaic land-allotment to make a radical claim about the nature of David's true possession. In the ancient Near East — and specifically under the Mosaic covenant — land was the primary form of security, identity, and inheritance. To have a portion (*manah*), a lot (*goral*), and a heritage (*nachalah*) was to have a stake in the covenant's blessings. The tribe of Levi was the one exception: they received no territorial allotment because Yahweh Himself was their portion (Num 18:20; Deut 10:9). David, who is not a Levite, applies the Levitical principle to himself — and by extension to every trusting heart.\n\nThe practical implication is significant. This psalm does not teach that earthly circumstances do not matter or that poverty is spiritually superior to wealth. It teaches that the measure of one's inheritance is not what one holds in the world but who one holds as Lord. 'The lines have fallen to me in pleasant places' (v.6) may coexist with material scarcity — the 'pleasant places' are defined not by comfortable coordinates but by the God who is the contents of the inheritance. The measuring-line could mark a narrow, rocky plot; it would still be 'beautiful' if Yahweh is what the plot contains.\n\nSwindoll observes that this is precisely where Western Christianity fails the test of Psalm 16 — we are trained to evaluate the beauty of our heritage by what we have rather than by who has us. The psalm reorients the metric entirely. The cup (*kos*) — the vessel of one's allotted experience (cf. Ps 23:5; Jesus's Gethsemane 'cup' in Matt 26:39) — is declared full and good not because David's circumstances are easy but because the One who 'supports his lot' (v.5b, *tamakh*, 'upholds, sustains') is Yahweh.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Goral* (lot, v.5) is the sacred casting-stone by which Joshua assigned territory — not random chance but divine direction. *Chevel* (measuring line, v.6) is the surveyor's cord; its 'falling in pleasant places' images God's direct hand in setting the boundaries of the psalmist's life. *Nachalah* (heritage/inheritance, v.6) is the standard OT word for the Promised Land as covenant inheritance — its application here to God Himself is a deliberate theological transfer."
