        "body": "Verse 7 introduces a new experiential register: gratitude for divine counsel. David does not merely acknowledge God as sovereign — he blesses God for being his personal advisor, the one who speaks into the specific situations of his life. The word *yaats* (counsel) is used of the wisest human advisors (2 Sam 16:23, of Ahithophel, 'as if one inquired of the word of God') and of the messianic title 'Wonderful Counselor' (Isa 9:6). That God condescends to counsel the individual believer is itself an act of grace worth gratitude.\n\nThe night-instruction of the *kilyah* ('kidneys,' translated 'mind' in NASB, 'heart' in ESV) is particularly striking. The kidneys in Hebrew anthropology were understood as the seat of deep emotion, moral sensitivity, and inner conscience — what we might call the deep interior. In nighttime stillness, when external noise withdraws, this inner faculty instructs. The practical pattern is familiar from Psalm 63:6 ('I meditate on You in the night watches') and Psalm 119:148 ('My eyes anticipate the night watches, that I may meditate on Your word'). The night is not wasted for the soul attentive to God; it is a school.\n\nVerse 8 names the discipline that makes such counsel possible: 'I have set the Lord continually before me.' The verb *shavah* (to set, place) and the adverb *tamid* (always, perpetually) together describe a habitual and deliberate practice — not an occasional burst of devotion but a sustained re-orienting of attention toward God. Hendricks would call this the interpretive framework that changes how everything else is read: when God is 'before you' continuously, every circumstance is processed through the lens of His character rather than the lens of your fear.\n\nThe logical consequence is stated in the second half of verse 8: 'Because He is at my right hand, I will not be shaken.' The right hand is the position of the guardian-warrior, the one who stands beside you in battle. The 'not shaken' (*mot*, to totter, to slip) recalls the Psalter's language for the righteous man who is established (Ps 15:5; 46:5; 55:22). Stability is not a temperamental achievement; it is the fruit of sustained attention to the Presence. Verse 9 then draws the experiential corollary in three coordinated members: heart, tongue, and body all participate in the joy that flows from this settled confidence. The integration signals that biblical joy is not a private interior state — it is an embodied, communicated reality.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kilyah* (kidneys, v.7, rendered 'mind' NASB) is the deep interior faculty — Hebrew anthropology located moral sensitivity and deepest emotion there (Jer 11:20; Ps 7:9). *Tamid* (always, v.8) is the same word used of the 'continual burnt offering' (Exod 29:42) — the perpetual sacrificial fire that never went out. Setting God before oneself *tamid* has that quality of unbroken maintenance."
