        "title": "The resurrection claim — death overturned, joy without end (vv.10-11)",
        "range": "16:10-11",
        "excerpt": "For You will not abandon my soul to Sheol; nor will You allow Your Holy One to undergo decay. You will make known to me the path of life; in Your presence is fullness of joy; in Your right hand there are pleasures forever.",
        "body": "Verses 10-11 are the psalm's climax and its most theologically freighted lines. Verse 10 makes two parallel negative claims: God will not abandon the soul to Sheol, and God will not allow His Holy One (*chasid*, the faithfully devoted one) to see decay (*shachat*, the pit or corruption). On David's lips, these lines expressed confidence in God's preservation through a particular mortal danger — that God would not let him be consumed by the realm of the dead before his time. That reading is real and not to be discarded.\n\nBut Peter at Pentecost (Acts 2:25-31) and Paul at Antioch (Acts 13:35-37) both stop at these verses and refuse to let them settle in David alone. Their argument is not creative interpretation but grammatical observation: David, the speaker, 'died and was buried, and his tomb is with us to this day' (Acts 2:29). He did experience decay. Therefore the claim that 'Your Holy One will not see decay' overflows its Davidic speaker and requires a resurrection that David did not personally experience. Peter concludes: 'Being therefore a prophet, and knowing that God had sworn with an oath to him that he would set one of his descendants on his throne, he foresaw and spoke about the resurrection of the Christ' (Acts 2:30-31 ESV).\n\nThis is sensus plenior — the fuller meaning that the divine author embedded in the text beyond the human author's full awareness. David's confident hope in God's preservation was genuinely his; the Spirit who inspired the words also pointed them toward their fullest referent. The apostolic reading does not evacuate the psalm of its Davidic meaning; it completes it. Christ is the head of the covenant community David celebrates in verse 3, the perfect embodiment of the trust David practices in verses 7-8, and the One in whom verse 10 is literally and completely fulfilled at the empty tomb.\n\nVerse 11 opens the eternal horizon: 'the path of life' (*orach chay*) leads directly to the presence of God (*paneh*, face/presence), where 'fullness of joy' (*sova simchah*, saturation with joy) and 'pleasures forever' (*naim netsach*, endless delight) await. The right hand of verse 8 — where God stood as guardian — becomes in verse 11 the right hand where the honored one stands in God's presence. The guardian becomes the host; mortal danger becomes eternal delight. Edwards captured this in *Religious Affections*: the joy of heaven is not the absence of difficulty but the unmediated presence of God. Psalm 16:11 is the Old Testament's most concentrated statement of that truth.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chasid* (Holy One, v.10) — the one characterized by *chesed* (covenant love, loyal faithfulness). The LXX renders it *hosios* (Acts 2:27 quotes the LXX), and both Greek and Hebrew carry the sense of 'the one devoted to God with holy loyalty.' *Shachat* (decay, pit) — used both for the physical dissolution of a body and for Sheol as a pit of destruction. *Netsach* (forever, v.11) — enduring, perpetual, without cessation; the same word used in Lamentations 3:18 ('my strength and my hope in the LORD have perished') and then reversed here: what perished in lament becomes eternal in hope."
